The **UTxO Indexer pattern** is a technique where the off-chain code passes explicit indices (positions in `self.inputs` or `self.outputs`) via the redeemer, instead of having the on-chain validator search through lists to find relevant UTxOs.

**Why it matters:**
- Cardano's on-chain execution is metered by CPU and memory units. `list.find` or repeated `list.filter` over large input/output sets is expensive.
- By accepting `input_index: Int` and `output_index: Int` in the redeemer, the validator can do a single O(n) `list.at` lookup instead of a full predicate scan.

**Example usage in Aiken v3:**
```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

pub type Redeemer {
  input_index: Int,
  output_index: Int,
}

validator indexed_spend {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Void>,
    redeemer: Redeemer,
    own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let own_input = list.at(self.inputs, redeemer.input_index)
    let own_output = list.at(self.outputs, redeemer.output_index)
    when (own_input, own_output) is {
      (Some(i), Some(_o)) -> i.output_reference == own_ref
      _ -> False
    }
  }

  else(_) { fail }
}
```
This pattern is central to Anastasia Labs' library because it makes validators dramatically cheaper to execute when transactions involve many UTxOs.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

validator one_shot(utxo_ref: OutputReference) {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, _policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    list.any(
      self.inputs,
      fn(input) { input.output_reference == utxo_ref },
    )
  }

  else(_) {
    fail
  }
}
```

Este es el patrón 'one-shot NFT': al parametrizar el validador con una `OutputReference` específica y exigir que ese UTxO sea consumido en la transacción de acuñación, se garantiza que el script sólo puede ejecutarse con éxito una vez. Una vez gastado ese UTxO, ya no existe en la cadena y ninguna transacción futura podrá satisfacer la condición.

