  mint(redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // "foo" == #[0x66, 0x6f, 0x6f] == #[102, 111, 111] in Aiken
    let expected_name: ByteArray = "foo"
    assets.quantity_of(self.mint, policy_id, expected_name) == 1
  }
}
```

Here `"foo"` is a UTF-8 encoded `ByteArray`, identical to `#[0x66, 0x6f, 0x6f]`. It is passed directly as an `AssetName` to `assets.quantity_of`, which confirms exactly one token with that name is minted.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator check_redeemer {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    redeemer: ByteArray,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    _self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    // "foo" es equivalente a #[0x66, 0x6f, 0x6f] en Aiken
    redeemer == "foo"
  }
}
```

El literal `"foo"` se codifica en UTF-8 como `#[0x66, 0x6f, 0x6f]` (`#[102, 111, 111]` en decimal). Usar la sintaxis de cadena hace el código más legible sin cambiar el valor subyacente de tipo `ByteArray`.

```aiken
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

validator foo_mint {
  mint(redeemer: Void, policy_id: ByteArray, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let asset_name: ByteArray = #"666f6f"
    assets.quantity_of(self.mint, policy_id, asset_name) == 1
  }
}
```

Here `#"666f6f"` is decoded at compile time to the 3-byte sequence `#[0x66, 0x6f, 0x6f]` (equivalent to the UTF-8 string `"foo"`). This is the correct way to embed a known binary asset name as a hex literal in Aiken. Using `"666f6f"` without the `#` prefix would produce a 6-byte array of ASCII codes — a completely different asset name.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

