En cada iteración, se accede al segundo elemento del `Pair` con la sintaxis `.2nd` y se acumula en el total. `list.foldl` recorre la lista de izquierda a derecha partiendo del valor inicial `0`.

```aiken
/// Extract the first element of a list, if any.
fn get_head(xs: List<a>) -> Option<a> {
  when xs is {
    [] -> None
    [head, ..] -> Some(head)
  }
}
```

`Option<a>` is built-in in Aiken. Pattern matching on the list with `when xs is` lets you handle the empty case (`[]`) returning `None`, and the non-empty case (`[head, ..]`) returning `Some(head)`.

input:
```aiken
fn find_positive(n: Int) -> Int {
  if n <= 0 {
    -1
  } else {
    n
  }
}
```

output:
Instead of returning `-1` as a sentinel, use `Option<Int>` to clearly express the absence of a valid value:

```aiken
/// Ensures a number is strictly positive.
fn to_positive(n: Int) -> Option<Int> {
  if n <= 0 {
    None
  } else {
    Some(n)
  }
}
```

This is safer and more idiomatic Aiken: callers are forced by the type system to handle both the `Some(value)` and `None` cases explicitly, eliminating the risk of misinterpreting `-1` as a real result.

En Aiken, `Option<a>` es un tipo genérico con dos constructores:

```aiken
type Option<a> {
  Some(a)
  None
}
```

Se usa cuando una función puede o no retornar un valor. Por ejemplo, para obtener el primer elemento de una lista:

```aiken
/// Obtiene el primer elemento de una lista, si existe.
fn get_head(xs: List<a>) -> Option<a> {
  when xs is {
    [] -> None
    [head, ..] -> Some(head)
  }
}
```

Si la lista está vacía, retorna `None`. Si tiene elementos, retorna `Some(head)`. El tipo `Option` está disponible por defecto en Aiken sin necesidad de importaciones.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, Input, OutputReference}
use aiken/collection/list

validator my_validator {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Data>,
    _redeemer: Data,
    own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let target_tx_id: ByteArray = #"deadbeef"

    let found: Option<Input> =
      list.find(
        self.inputs,
        fn(input) { input.output_reference.transaction_id == target_tx_id },
      )

    when found is {
      Some(_input) -> True
      None -> False
    }
  }
}
```

`list.find` returns `Option<Input>` — `Some(input)` if a match exists, or `None` otherwise. Pattern matching on the result lets you handle both cases explicitly and safely, returning `False` when no matching input is found.

```aiken
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

const required_signer: VerificationKeyHash = #"deadbeefdeadbeefdeadbeefdeadbeefdeadbeefdeadbeefdeadbeef"

validator no_datum_spend {
  spend(datum: Option<Never>, _redeemer: Data, _own_ref: OutputReference, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // datum can only ever be None (Never serialises identically to None)
    when datum is {
      None -> list.has(self.extra_signatories, required_signer)
      Some(_) -> False
    }
  }
}
```

Because `Never` has only one constructor (which serialises the same as `None`), wrapping it in `Option<Never>` means the datum can only ever be `None`. Any attempt to construct a `Some(Never)` at the type level is impossible, reinforcing that no meaningful datum exists on these UTxOs.

```aiken
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

const owner: VerificationKeyHash = #"aabbccddaabbccddaabbccddaabbccddaabbccddaabbccddaabbccdd"

validator always_none_mint {
  mint(_redeemer: Never, _policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // Never serializa igual que None; no hay redeemer significativo
    list.has(self.extra_signatories, owner)
  }
}
```

Al declarar el redeemer como `Never`, se comunica explícitamente que este minting policy no necesita ningún dato en el redeemer. Dado que `Never` serializa idéntico a `None` en binario, cualquier transacción que pase `None` como redeemer será aceptada por el ledger sin problemas.

input:
```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

const admin: VerificationKeyHash = #"cafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafe"

validator legacy_spend {
  spend(datum: Option<Data>, _redeemer: Data, _own_ref: OutputReference, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      None -> list.has(self.extra_signatories, admin)
      Some(_) -> False
    }
  }
}
```

output:
Usando `Option<Never>` se expresa explícitamente que el datum **nunca puede contener un valor significativo**. Dado que `Never` serializa igual que `None`, la compatibilidad on-chain se mantiene intacta.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

const admin: VerificationKeyHash = #"cafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafecafe"

validator refactored_spend {
  spend(datum: Option<Never>, _redeemer: Data, _own_ref: OutputReference, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // Option<Never> solo puede ser None; Some(Never) no es construible
    when datum is {
      None -> list.has(self.extra_signatories, admin)
      Some(_) -> False
    }
  }
}
```

**Cambios realizados:**
- `Option<Data>` → `Option<Never>`: comunica que el datum no lleva información real.
- La lógica y la compatibilidad binaria permanecen iguales, ya que `Never` serializa idéntico a `None` a nivel `Data`.

Puedes definir una función de comparación personalizada usando el tipo `Ordering` de la siguiente manera:

```aiken
pub fn compare_ints(a: Int, b: Int) -> Ordering {
  if a < b {
    Less
  } else if a == b {
    Equal
  } else {
    Greater
  }
}
```

Esta función devuelve `Less` si `a` es menor que `b`, `Equal` si son iguales, y `Greater` si `a` es mayor. Puedes usar esta función como argumento en `list.sort` para ordenar una lista de enteros:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

let sorted = list.sort([3, 1, 2], compare_ints)
```

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/primitive/bytearray
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

pub type Datum {
  asset_names: List<ByteArray>,
}

validator sorted_asset_names {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Datum>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    _self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      None -> False
      Some(d) -> {
        let names = d.asset_names
        let sorted = list.sort(names, bytearray.compare)
        names == sorted
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This validator extracts the `asset_names` from the datum and checks that sorting it with `bytearray.compare` (which returns `Ordering`) produces the same list, confirming it is already in ascending lexicographic order.

Puedes usar una expresión `when` para hacer pattern matching sobre un valor de tipo `Ordering` y manejar cada uno de los tres constructores:

```aiken
use aiken/primitive/bytearray

fn describe_comparison(a: ByteArray, b: ByteArray) -> ByteArray {
  when bytearray.compare(a, b) is {
    Less -> "a es menor que b"
    Equal -> "a es igual a b"
    Greater -> "a es mayor que b"
  }
}
```

El tipo `Ordering` tiene exactamente tres constructores: `Less`, `Equal` y `Greater`. Al usar `when ... is`, el compilador de Aiken verificará que hayas cubierto todos los casos, garantizando exhaustividad.

input:
```aiken
fn is_sorted(xs: List<Int>) -> Bool {
  when xs is {
    [] -> True
    [_] -> True
    [a, b, ..rest] -> a <= b && is_sorted([b, ..rest])
  }
}
```

output:
You can refactor this by using `list.sort` with a custom integer comparator and comparing the result to the original list:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

fn compare_ints(a: Int, b: Int) -> Ordering {
  if a < b {
    Less
  } else if a == b {
    Equal
  } else {
    Greater
  }
}

fn is_sorted(xs: List<Int>) -> Bool {
  xs == list.sort(xs, compare_ints)
}
```

This approach leverages `list.sort`, which accepts a `fn(a, a) -> Ordering` comparator, to produce a sorted copy of the list. If the original list equals the sorted version, it is already in order. The `Ordering` type makes the comparator contract explicit and reusable.

In Aiken, `Void` is the primitive type representing the nullary constructor — essentially the absence of a value. It is both a type and a constructor, denoted by the same name `Void`.

Conceptually, if you think in terms of tuples, `Void` is a tuple with zero elements. It is analogous to `()` (unit) in languages like Haskell or Rust.

**When to use it:**
- As a redeemer type when a script doesn't need any redeemer data:
```aiken
validator my_validator {
  spend(datum: Option<Void>, redeemer: Void, own_ref: OutputReference, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    True
  }
}
```
- As the callback return type for side-effectful iteration functions like `list.for_each`, which has the signature `pub fn for_each(self: List<a>, do: fn(a) -> Void) -> Void`.

Because Aiken is fully expression-based (no statements), `Void` is rarely needed in practice, but it cleanly represents "no meaningful value" in typed contexts.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator always_true {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    _self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    True
  }
}
```

Here, `Void` is used as the redeemer type to signal that no redeemer data is required. The validator unconditionally returns `True`, making it an "always succeed" script. Using `Void` keeps the on-chain footprint minimal since the redeemer carries no information.

In the Aiken standard library, `Void` appears as the return type of `list.for_each`:

```aiken
pub fn for_each(self: List<a>, do: fn(a) -> Void) -> Void
```

This function is used when you want to iterate over a list purely for its side effects (e.g., tracing), without producing a new list. The callback must return `Void`, and the function itself also returns `Void`.

**Example:**
```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

fn log_items(items: List<Int>) -> Void {
  list.for_each(items, fn(item) {
    // perform some side-effectful operation per item
    Void
  })
}
```

Because Aiken is fully typed and expression-based, `Void` serves as the explicit type for "no meaningful return value", analogous to `unit` in other functional languages.

```aiken
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

validator my_minting_policy {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let asset_name = "my_token"
    let minted_qty =
      assets.quantity_of(self.mint, policy_id, asset_name)
    minted_qty == 1
  }
}
```

Aquí se usa `Void` como tipo del redeemer para indicar que no se necesita ningún dato adicional al momento de acuñar. La lógica verifica que la cantidad acuñada del token `my_token` bajo esta política sea exactamente 1, usando `assets.quantity_of` sobre `self.mint`.

`Void` es poco frecuente en Aiken porque el lenguaje es completamente basado en expresiones: toda construcción sintáctica retorna un valor con un tipo. No existen "sentencias" sin valor de retorno como en lenguajes imperativos.

**¿Por qué raramente se necesita?**
En la mayoría de los casos, las funciones retornan tipos concretos como `Bool`, `Int`, `Option<a>`, etc. No hay necesidad de un tipo "vacío" en lógica de validación normal.

**¿Cuándo sí tiene sentido usarlo?**

1. **Como tipo de redeemer en validadores simples**, cuando el script no necesita información del redeemer:
```aiken
validator simple {
  spend(_datum: Option<Void>, _redeemer: Void, _ref: OutputReference, _tx: Transaction) -> Bool {
    True
  }
}
```

2. **Como tipo de retorno en funciones de iteración con efectos**, como `list.for_each`:
```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

fn procesar(items: List<Int>) -> Void {
  list.for_each(items, fn(_item) { Void })
}
```

En ambos casos, `Void` comunica explícitamente que no hay datos significativos involucrados.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction, InlineDatum}
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}

pub type MyDatum {
  owner: VerificationKeyHash
  amount: Int
}

validator my_spend_validator {
  spend(
    datum: Option<MyDatum>,
    _redeemer: Data,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    // datum is already decoded by the handler — just unwrap it
    when datum is {
      Some(d) -> {
        // Custom logic: amount must be positive and owner must have signed
        let owner_signed =
          list.has(self.extra_signatories, d.owner)
        let valid_amount = d.amount > 0
        owner_signed && valid_amount
      }
      None -> fail
    }
  }
}
```

**Key points about `Data` and typed datums:**
- In Aiken v3 `spend` handlers, the datum parameter `Option<T>` is automatically decoded from the raw `Data` stored on-chain.
- If decoding fails (the raw `Data` doesn't match `MyDatum`'s shape), the script fails safely — no silent mismatch.
- `self.datums` (a `Dict<DataHash, Data>`) holds hashed datums; inline datums are surfaced directly through the typed `datum` parameter.
- `Data` itself is opaque — you cannot inspect it structurally without a `when … is` cast to a concrete type.

```aiken
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

pub type MintAction {
  MintTokens { qty: Int }
  BurnTokens
}

validator token_policy {
  mint(redeemer: MintAction, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // Aiken v3 decodes the redeemer Data into MintAction automatically.
    // If decoding fails the script fails safely.
    when redeemer is {
      MintTokens { qty } -> {
        // Must request a positive quantity
        let positive_qty = qty > 0
        // All minted tokens under this policy must be positive
        let minted_positive =
          assets.tokens(self.mint, policy_id)
            |> dict.values
            |> list.all(fn(q) { q > 0 })
        positive_qty && minted_positive
      }
      BurnTokens -> {
        // All tokens under this policy must be negative (burning)
        assets.tokens(self.mint, policy_id)
          |> dict.values
          |> list.all(fn(q) { q < 0 })
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Notas sobre `Data` y redeemers:**
- El redeemer llega desde la cadena como `Data` opaco; el handler `mint` de Aiken v3 lo decodifica al tipo concreto `MintAction` automáticamente.
- Si el `Data` recibido no coincide con la forma de `MintAction`, el script falla de forma segura.
- `self.mint` es de tipo `Value` y `assets.tokens/2` devuelve un `Dict<AssetName, Int>` con las cantidades bajo la policy dada.

Because `Data` can represent *any* serialisable value, it acts as the common element type for a heterogeneous list.

```aiken
pub type Foo {
  x: Int
}

pub type Bar {
  y: ByteArray
}

// Build a heterogeneous list by casting each value to Data
let items: List<Data> = [
  (Foo { x: 42 } : Data),
  (Bar { y: #"deadbeef" } : Data),
  (Foo { x: 7 } : Data),
]

// Retrieve and process each element with a safe cast
let results: List<Int> =
  list.filter_map(
    items,
    fn(item) {
      when item is {
        f: Foo -> Some(f.x)   // only keep Foo values
        _ -> None
      }
    },
  )
// results == [42, 7]
```

**Why this works:**
- Any user-defined type is implicitly castable *to* `Data`.
- Casting *from* `Data` via `when … is` is safe: a non-matching branch returns `None` (or you can `fail`) instead of crashing silently.
- `list.filter_map` (stdlib) is perfect here — it maps and filters in one pass, discarding `None` results.

**Caveat:** You lose static type-safety inside the list. Prefer concrete types when all elements share the same shape; use `Data` only when genuine heterogeneity is required.

```aiken
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

type Datum {
  owner: VerificationKeyHash,
}

validator my_validator {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Datum>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    trace @"spend: validator invoked"
    when datum is {
      None -> {
        trace @"spend: no datum found, rejecting"
        False
      }
      Some(d) -> {
        trace @"spend: checking owner signature"
        let signed = list.has(self.extra_signatories, d.owner)
        if signed {
          trace @"spend: owner signature verified"
          True
        } else {
          trace @"spend: owner signature missing"
          False
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

```aiken
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

const authorized_minter: VerificationKeyHash =
  #"abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef12"

validator nft_policy {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, _policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    trace @"mint: validator invoked"
    let is_authorized =
      list.has(self.extra_signatories, authorized_minter)
    if is_authorized {
      trace @"mint: authorized signer found, allowing mint"
      True
    } else {
      trace @"mint: unauthorized, rejecting mint"
      False
    }
  }
}
```

Use `list.any` on `self.extra_signatories` to check whether at least one signer matches your approved list:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

fn has_approved_signer(
  approved: List<VerificationKeyHash>,
  self: Transaction,
) -> Bool {
  list.any(self.extra_signatories, fn(signer) { list.has(approved, signer) })
}
```

`list.any` returns `True` as soon as the predicate matches one element, making it efficient for this check.

Usa `assets.quantity_of` para obtener la cantidad de un token específico dentro de un `Value`:

```aiken
use cardano/assets

fn token_amount(
  v: assets.Value,
  policy: assets.PolicyId,
  name: assets.AssetName,
) -> Int {
  assets.quantity_of(v, policy, name)
}
```

Esta función devuelve `0` si el token no está presente en el valor, por lo que es segura de llamar sin verificación previa.

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

const deadline: Int = 1_800_000_000_000

validator time_locked_mint {
  mint(redeemer: Void, _policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    interval.is_entirely_before(self.validity_range, deadline)
  }
}
```

`interval.is_entirely_before(self.validity_range, deadline)` returns `True` only when the entire validity range lies strictly before the deadline, preventing any mint from succeeding at or after that point.

Use `list.foldl` combined with `assets.lovelace_of` to accumulate the lovelace from each output:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{Output, Transaction}

fn total_lovelace(self: Transaction) -> Int {
  list.foldl(
    self.outputs,
    0,
    fn(output: Output, acc: Int) -> Int {
      acc + assets.lovelace_of(output.value)
    },
  )
}
```

`list.foldl` iterates left-to-right over the outputs, accumulating the lovelace amount starting from `0`.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

pub type Datum {
  owner: VerificationKeyHash,
}

validator owner_spend {
  spend(
    datum: Option<Datum>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      Some(d) -> list.has(self.extra_signatories, d.owner)
      None -> False
    }
  }
}
```

`list.has` checks whether the owner's `VerificationKeyHash` appears in `self.extra_signatories`. If no datum is present the validator rejects the transaction.

Since `Pairs<Credential, Lovelace>` is just `List<Pair<Credential, Lovelace>>`, you can use `list.any` from `aiken/collection/list` to search for the credential:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}
use cardano/address.{Credential}

fn has_withdrawal(self: Transaction, cred: Credential) -> Bool {
  list.any(self.withdrawals, fn(pair) { pair.1st == cred })
}
```

Here, `pair.1st` accesses the key (the `Credential`) of each `Pair`, and `pair.2nd` would give the `Lovelace` amount. Because `Pairs` is a plain `List`, all `list` functions apply directly.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, ScriptPurpose, Withdraw}
use cardano/address.{Credential}

validator guard_withdrawal {
  withdraw(_redeemer: Void, account: Credential, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    list.any(
      self.redeemers,
      fn(pair) {
        when pair.1st is {
          Withdraw(cred) -> cred == account
          _ -> False
        }
      },
    )
  }
}
```

This iterates over `self.redeemers`, which is typed as `Pairs<ScriptPurpose, Redeemer>` — a `List<Pair<ScriptPurpose, Redeemer>>`. It checks whether any entry has a `Withdraw` purpose matching the withdrawing `account` credential.

Porque `Pairs<a, b>` es simplemente un alias de tipo definido como `List<Pair<a, b>>`. Al ser equivalente a una lista, todas las funciones del módulo `aiken/collection/list` — incluyendo `list.filter`, `list.map`, `list.foldl`, `list.any`, etc. — funcionan directamente sobre valores de tipo `Pairs`.

Por ejemplo, para filtrar todas las entradas de `self.redeemers` que correspondan a propósitos `Mint`:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{ScriptPurpose, Mint}

let mint_redeemers =
  list.filter(
    self.redeemers,
    fn(pair) {
      when pair.1st is {
        Mint(_) -> True
        _ -> False
      }
    },
  )
```

No se necesita ninguna conversión especial: `Pairs` y `List` son el mismo tipo subyacente.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, ScriptPurpose, Mint}

validator single_mint {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    let mint_purposes =
      list.filter(
        self.redeemers,
        fn(pair) {
          when pair.1st is {
            Mint(_) -> True
            _ -> False
          }
        },
      )
    list.length(mint_purposes) == 1 && list.any(
      mint_purposes,
      fn(pair) {
        when pair.1st is {
          Mint(pid) -> pid == policy_id
          _ -> False
        }
      },
    )
  }
}
```

Aquí se itera `self.redeemers` (de tipo `Pairs<ScriptPurpose, Redeemer>`) usando `list.filter` y `list.any`, ya que `Pairs` es simplemente `List<Pair<...>>`.

Como `Pairs<Credential, Lovelace>` es equivalente a `List<Pair<Credential, Lovelace>>`, puedes usar `list.foldl` directamente para acumular todos los montos de Lovelace:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

fn total_withdrawals(self: Transaction) -> Int {
  list.foldl(
    self.withdrawals,
    0,
    fn(pair, acc) { acc + pair.2nd },
  )
}
```

En cada iteración, `pair.1st` es el `Credential` y `pair.2nd` es el monto en `Lovelace` (un alias de `Int`). El acumulador comienza en `0` y se va sumando cada valor. Esto funciona sin conversiones porque `Pairs` no es más que una lista estándar de Aiken.

En el framework de pruebas basadas en propiedades de Aiken, `PRNG` y `Fuzzer` tienen roles complementarios:

- **`PRNG`** (Generador de Números Pseudoaleatorios): Es el motor interno de aleatoriedad. Su definición es opaca, lo que significa que el framework lo gestiona de forma transparente. Tú nunca necesitas instanciar ni manipular un `PRNG` directamente.

- **`Fuzzer`**: Es la interfaz pública que usas para construir generadores de datos aleatorios. Un `Fuzzer<a>` describe *cómo* generar valores aleatorios de tipo `a`. Internamente, un `Fuzzer` consume un `PRNG` para producir sus valores, pero esta dependencia está abstraída.

La relación es: el `PRNG` provee la semilla de aleatoriedad, y el `Fuzzer` la transforma en valores de tipos concretos (enteros, listas, bytes, etc.). Los `Fuzzer`s están diseñados para componerse entre sí, permitiéndote construir generadores complejos a partir de primitivas simples.

Ejemplo conceptual:
```aiken
// fuzz.int() devuelve un Fuzzer<Int>
// fuzz.list(fuzz.int()) devuelve un Fuzzer<List<Int>>
test mi_propiedad(xs via fuzz.list(fuzz.int())) {
  list.length(xs) >= 0
}
```

Yes, `G1Element` and `G2Element` are valid Aiken primitive types you can use in redeemers or datums. They are consumed by BLS12-381 builtin functions. Here is a mint validator that accepts a `G1Element` proof in its redeemer:

```aiken
use aiken/builtin

pub type BlsRedeemer {
  proof: G1Element,
}

validator bls_mint_example {
  mint(redeemer: BlsRedeemer, _policy_id: PolicyId, _self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // Actual BLS verification would use builtin BLS12-381 functions.
    // Here we just confirm the proof field is present and non-trivially accessible.
    let _proof: G1Element = redeemer.proof
    True
  }
}
```

> **Note:** Real BLS12-381 operations (e.g., `builtin.bls12_381_g1_equal`, pairing checks) are described in CIP-0381 and are invoked via Aiken's `builtin` module. The types `G1Element`, `G2Element`, and `MillerLoopResult` are Aiken primitive types recognized by the compiler for use with those builtins.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

pub type BlsDatum {
  public_key: G2Element,
}

validator bls_spend {
  spend(
    datum: Option<BlsDatum>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    _self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      Some(d) -> {
        // The G2Element is present in the datum; proceed with any BLS logic.
        let _pk: G2Element = d.public_key
        True
      }
      None -> False
    }
  }
}
```

`G2Element` is a first-class Aiken primitive type. You can store it in a datum or redeemer just like any other type. Actual cryptographic operations on the `G2Element` (e.g., pairing checks) would use the BLS12-381 builtin functions described in CIP-0381.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator fee_check {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let max_fee = 2_000_000
    let actual_fee = self.fee
    actual_fee <= max_fee
  }
}
```

Here `let max_fee` and `let actual_fee` are immutable let-bindings used to give readable names to the constant threshold and the transaction fee before comparing them.

```aiken
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

validator single_mint {
  mint(
    _redeemer: Void,
    policy_id: assets.PolicyId,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let asset_name = #"746f6b656e"
    let minted_qty = assets.quantity_of(self.mint, policy_id, asset_name)
    let expected_qty = 1
    minted_qty == expected_qty
  }
}
```

Se utilizan tres let-bindings:
- `asset_name`: nombre del token que se quiere acuñar.
- `minted_qty`: cantidad realmente acuñada obtenida de `self.mint`.
- `expected_qty`: constante que representa la cantidad permitida.

Al ser inmutables, ninguno de estos valores puede cambiar una vez declarado.

En Aiken, las constantes de módulo se declaran con la palabra clave `const`. No se permiten enlaces `let` en el nivel superior del módulo. Las constantes son inmutables, se evalúan completamente en tiempo de compilación y el compilador las incrusta (inline) en cada lugar donde se usan.

```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}
use aiken/interval

const start_year = 2101
const end_year = 2111

validator year_range_check {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    // Usa las constantes igual que literales
    let valid_range = interval.between(start_year, end_year)
    interval.contains(valid_range, start_year)
  }
}
```

Las constantes `start_year` y `end_year` pueden usarse en cualquier lugar donde escribirías un literal, incluyendo expresiones `when`, `if/else` y llamadas a funciones.

input:
```aiken
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}
use cardano/assets

validator token_threshold {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let total_inputs =
      self.inputs
        |> list.length
    total_inputs >= 3 && total_inputs <= 10
  }
}
